    <title>Combined summary - Detailed protocol design for routed multi-transaction CoinSwap</title>
    <updated>2023-06-14T03:30:04.757539+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2020-September/018157.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>CoinSwap is a privacy-focused protocol that enables two parties to exchange coins without revealing their identities. The protocol includes multi-transaction CoinSwaps, routed CoinSwaps, liquidity market, private key handover, and fidelity bonds. While the protocol provides a high degree of privacy, there are still concerns about potential attacks and accidents. To address these issues, various solutions have been proposed by different developers.The email conversation between Antoine Riard and Chris Belcher discusses potential vulnerabilities in the design of CoinSwap, proposing solutions to address issues related to fee malleability and transaction pinning attacks. The technical details of the protocol are also discussed, describing how staggered timelocks and EC tweaks can be used to ensure all parties receive their coins back. Chris Belcher's implementation of CoinSwap includes multiple features such as multi-transaction CoinSwaps, routed CoinSwaps, liquidity market, private key handover, and fidelity bonds.ZmnSCPxj highlights certain vulnerabilities in the Lightning Network and potential attack scenarios. The email thread provides a detailed analysis of the CoinSwap protocol and its potential deviations, offering solutions and recommendations to ensure the privacy and security of all parties involved.Antoine and ZmnSCPxj recommend various techniques to reduce risks in transaction processes. They suggest swapping A-&gt;B-&gt;A and then A-&gt;C-&gt;A as a way to mitigate risks associated with the use of intermediary parties. Additionally, they recommend using contract transactions with relative timelocks, which can be utilized to help prevent theft by offline takers.The discussion also focuses on enhancing the CoinSwap protocol with PayJoin-with-CoinSwap and 2p-ECDSA with Scriptless Script. PayJoin is a privacy-enhancing technique that allows for multiple participants to make transactions together, making it more difficult for third parties to track individual transactions. The 2p-ECDSA with Scriptless Script is a trust-minimized solution that can be used to further increase security while reducing the need for multi-signatures.One key risk in the transaction process is the possibility of funds being stolen by takers who have been offline for too long. However, Antoine and ZmnSCPxj recommend mitigating this risk through the use of a timelock and the scriptless script 2p-ECDSA. Overall, Antoine and ZmnSCPxj's discussion highlights innovative approaches to address the inherent risks in cryptocurrency transactions. By using these techniques, individuals can better secure their financial assets while conducting transactions in a privacy-enhanced, trust-minimized manner.</summary>
